# Code Style

## Fields

Fields go at the top of the class, always. Order: static fields first, then instance fields.

```java
private static final int SESSION_TOKEN_BYTES = 32;

private final ServerRepository serverRepository;
@Setter(AccessLevel.NONE) private Long id;
private String serverName;
```

## Method Order

1. Constructors
2. `@Override` methods
3. Event handler methods
4. Public methods
5. Protected methods
6. Private methods
7. Public static methods
8. Protected static methods
9. Private static methods

## Lombok

Use Lombok to eliminate boilerplate. Apply annotations at class level where uniform, field level where access needs to differ.

```java
@Entity
@Table(name = "servers")
@NoArgsConstructor
@Getter @Setter
public class ServerRow {
    @Id @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    @Setter(AccessLevel.NONE)
    private Long id;

    @Column(name = "created_at", nullable = false)
    @Setter(AccessLevel.NONE)
    private Instant createdAt;
}
```

- Use `@Getter` / `@Setter` at class level when all fields share the same access.
- Use field-level `@Setter(AccessLevel.NONE)` for identity or immutable fields.
- Use `@UtilityClass` for static-only utility classes.
- Use `@Slf4j` for logging (not a manual logger or `@Log4j2`).
- Use `@SneakyThrows` when a checked exception can't realistically occur and wrapping it adds noise.

## Nullability

Only use `@Nullable` from JetBrains (`org.jetbrains.annotations.Nullable`) on fields or parameters that may be null.

Don't use `@NonNull`, `@NotNull`, or any other non-null annotation in our own code. The only exception is overriding a third-party API that already uses them.

## No Useless Variables or Methods

Don't assign a value to a variable if it's only used once immediately after. Don't extract a method if it's only called from one place and adds no clarity — inline it.

## Static Methods and Constants

Move general-purpose static methods to a `@UtilityClass` in `util`. Access `public static` fields directly — no getters.

```java
// bad
AuthUtils.getHashAlgorithm()

// good
AuthUtils.hash(value)
```

## Spring Conventions

- Constructor injection for services and controllers; no field injection.
- DTOs are Java `record`s with Jakarta validation annotations where needed.
- Services throw typed exceptions from `exception.impl`; `ExceptionControllerAdvice` maps them to HTTP responses.
- Use `@Transactional` on service methods that perform multiple writes.
- Controllers stay thin — delegate to services, no business logic.

## JPA and Migrations

- Entity table/column names use snake_case via `@Column(name = "...")`.
- One Flyway migration per schema change: `V{n}__short_description.sql`. Never edit applied migrations.
- Metric time-series rows live in `model.persistance.metric`; server/user rows in `model.persistance`.

## Performance

Metrics ingest is a hot path. Performance is not an afterthought.

- Prefer `HashMap` over `LinkedHashMap`, arrays over lists, primitives over boxed types where order and boxing don't matter.
- Avoid unnecessary object allocation in ingest handlers and frequently called service methods.
- Don't iterate a collection multiple times when one pass will do.
- Cache lookups repeated within the same operation rather than re-fetching.
- If two approaches are otherwise equal, pick the faster one.
